##Postmortem examination of a deceased person with NCP can reveal important information about the disease

Weixin Guokr42

Functional introductions, science and technology, are the language we speak to the world.

It took only a week for Chinese scientists to identify the virus after the COVID-19 outbreak last December. Since then, the world's academic journals have published the results of related clinical cases, but no death related autopsy results have been disclosed.

Liu Liang, a professor in the Department of Forensic Medicine at Tongji Medical College, recently called for an early, systematic autopsy of the dead cases of new pneumonia in the hope of a pathological breakthrough, in order to facilitate clinical diagnosis and development of targeted treatment program. 1

Professor Liu Liang, in an interview, offered a solution to the current autopsy conundrum, also referring to the | pear video from the SARS autopsy

Although we may be constrained by current anatomical and ethical considerations, we are not yet able to learn more about the new pneumonia from the autopsy. However, the current research progress suggests that the virus that caused this outbreak, SARS-CoV-2 and SARS-CoV, is a pair of sister flowers, similar genetic sequence.

After the SARS outbreak in 2003, forensic scientists performed autopsies on some of the deaths. Perhaps we can find some valuable experience from the autopsy results of SARS.
A cytokine storm,
May Be one of the important factors in the severe illness of SARS

SARS is a severe acute respiratory syndrome, onset is rapid, 3 to 7 days began to appear dry cough, blood sputum and other non-specific respiratory symptoms, 10 to 14 days to reach the peak, in addition to fever, weakness and other symptoms aggravated, most cases present with Acute respiratory distress syndrome, dyspnea, and other symptoms.

The main pathological changes in SARS patients are lung injury, but the lung injury is not only caused by direct virus attack, that is to say, there are other mechanisms leading to "secondary injury. ".

A paper on the anatomy of the lungs of six SARS victims in Hong Kong speculates on the mechanism of secondary lung injury.

The pathological changes observed on the anatomy included:

Microscopic examination of lung tissue revealed diffuse alveolar injury with bronchial epithelial exfoliation, loss of Cilia, squamous metaplasia, and Alveolar and interstitial macrophages infiltration in most of the deceased, the alveolar epithelial cells proliferate to form amphiphilic cytoplasm-rich multinucleated giant cells, or giant cell pneumonia. The large amount of exudation and infiltration of white blood cells resulted in a markedly swollen and enlarged lung with an increase in weight of 2.

(left) severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) pneumonia with partially giant-cell-forming Alveolar epithelial cells. Large amounts of fibrinous exudate are seen in the Alveoli. The alveolar walls of the lungs are capillary and the integrity of the alveolar walls is compromised

These respiratory system symptoms are caused by primary and secondary damage to the lungs caused by the virus. Three
Under Electron microscopy, 90-nanometer coronavirus particles were observed in the endoplasmic reticulum secretory vesicles of Type II alveolar epithelial cells
Based on these lung lesions, the authors speculate that the pulmonary phagocytosis in SARS patients suggests that cytokine imbalance may be an important factor leading to severe clinical symptoms in SARS patients. Three

Cytokine imbalance (now commonly known as a "cytokine storm") is an over-immune response in which the body secretes a large number of cytokines in a short period of time, causing systemic Inflammatory Response Syndrome and even multiple organ dysfunction. These cytokines can induce Lung injury-repair mechanisms activated, and ultimately lead to pulmonary fibrosis, which is one of the reasons patients end up with dyspnea and Acute respiratory distress syndrome. 5 The authors also believe that clinically appropriate glucocorticoid intervention can modulate cytokine imbalance and avoid fatal consequences. Three

Until now, the hormone therapy for SARS patients was still very controversial, and this anatomical result provides some evidence to support this plan.

The current treatment of new coronary pneumonia hormone intervention, there is a certain degree of controversy. If we can understand the immune response of coronaviruses in tissue cells by dissection, we believe that the results will guide the treatment.

Except for the lungs,
The SARS virus is still hiding in the gastrointestinal tract and so on

Another systematic anatomical study of 4 SARS and 4 non-SARS patients in Guangdong Province showed that SARS virus was found in sweat glands, kidneys, gastrointestinal tract, etc. . According to the authors, the results suggest that the SARS virus may be transmitted through fecal, sweat and urine as well as through respiratory transmission. Four

Later Clinical Studies also showed that viral nucleic acids could be detected in stool, urine or throat swabs within weeks of the onset of SARS, and even infectious viruses could be extracted. Six, seven

Sars-positive (Reddish Brown) small intestinal epithelium (3A) and negative control (3d) ; SARS-positive Sweat Gland Cells (8A) and negative control (8d) | Ref. 4

Had it been known earlier that the SARS virus could invade the gastrointestinal tract, cases like the one in Hong Kong's Amoy Gardens, where SARS spread in the community, might have been prevented. The new coronavirus nucleic acid can be detected in the stool of patients with COVID-19 pneumonia, suggesting the possibility of faecal-oral transmission. Recently, Academician Zhong Nanshan's team has also further extracted the active virus from the stool of patients.

If an in-depth autopsy can be performed, it could provide substantial evidence of how the virus is transmitted.
90 hours after death, there were no visible changes
Active SARS virus may still exist

A team of researchers from the Chinese University of Hong Kong performed systematic autopsies on 11 SARS patients who had suffered from a variety of illnesses. They analyzed the distribution of the virus in the patients'bodies by detecting the viral nucleic acid content in different organs. 8 The technology was dubbed a 'star' for the period -- real time quantitative PCR.

In addition to this technique, the paper attempts to isolate the virus from different organs and tissues in an attempt to understand how the virus behaves after death.

This may seem strange to some, but don't they both test for viral load? What difference does it make?

That's a big difference.

Viruses extracted from tissue are active and can infect people, while the extraction of viral nucleic acids from tissue does not mean that there are still infectious viruses in the tissue. It's like finding a live cat in Schr√∂dinger's box that bites, but if you find only cat hair, it means there was a cat in the box, but you can't be sure there wasn't another cat in the box that bit.

So there's no need to panic too much about the fact that doorknobs can extract information like viral nucleic acids. It's possible that this nucleic acid is already the remains of an uninfectious virus.

In this paper, we tried to extract the active virus from Cadaveric Lung, heart, kidney, liver, spleen, small intestine, psoas muscle and bone marrow more than 90 hours after death, results only active viruses with infectious ability were isolated from the small intestine (4 / 6) and Lung Tissue (4 / 11) . Active viruses can be isolated from the lungs of patients 175 hours after death and from the small intestine of patients 160 hours after death.

In some of the autopsied cases, the active virus was extracted from each organ and positive for infectious virus was found in the lung 175 hours after death and in the small intestine 160 hours after death. | Ref. 8

At the same time, the researchers measured viral nucleic acid levels in the organs or tissues and found that the median viral nucleic acid levels per gram of tissue in the small intestine and lungs were 600,000 to 170,000 times higher than in other organs or tissues. The authors speculate that although the virus would gradually die off after death, the viral content in the lungs and small intestine was already high, so the virus was not "completely wiped out" 90 hours after death.

According to these data, the mortician's protection and the follow-up treatment of the corpse are also very important after the death of the patient with the new coronavirus infection.

At the same time, the authors compared the changes of SARS-cov nucleic acid content in the above organs or tissues of the deceased with different course of disease, and found that except that the viral nucleic acid content in lung tissue decreased obviously from the 12th to 13th day after the onset of disease, other organs or tissues have relatively stable viral nucleic acid levels.

The authors speculate that it is possible that Ribavirin Andor glucocorticoid therapy has a more significant inhibitory effect on the pulmonary virus. Some scholars also believe that the decline in viral nucleic acid content in the lungs, is the body's immune system began to function as a result.

Lung SARS virus nucleic acid content (PCNA) , housekeeping gene (PCNA) , and SARS virus relative content (QNA) , cross-coordinate for the duration of illness onset-death. Each data point was from a different patient and represented an average of about the SARS virus nucleic acid content in the lungs. | Ref. 8

Why do we need to do a full workup
To perform a systematic autopsy?

From the above three articles on the anatomy of SARS victims, scientists have a general understanding of the disease caused by SARS in various organs and tissues of the human body, and understand the bias of SARS virus in various organs, and preliminarily speculate that SARS may cause cytokine imbalance.

As noted earlier, if it had been known that the SARS virus could accumulate in high concentrations in the gut, community transmission such as Amoy Gardens sewers might have been avoided. Of course, in the case of COVID-19 pneumonia, the researchers extracted the active virus from the patient's stool, speculating that the virus might be transmitted by faecal oral route, a lesson learned from the SARS battle.

The clinical symptoms of this case of COVID-19 pneumonia are different from those of SARS, and it is impossible to infer the pathogenesis, pathophysiology and route of transmission from the SARS study. Moreover, even now has various advanced molecular pathology technology, still can not intuitively understand the virus to the human body damage.

If it had not been for the deceased and their families who donated their bodies to advance SARS research, SARS related research would not have made the same progress as it does now.

At present, we know very little about NCP, and at a time when the epidemic was at its peak and the diagnosis and treatment were still incomplete, it is believed that if we could systematically dissect some of the dead, it will certainly help us understand the pathophysiological progression and pathogenesis of COVID-19 pneumonia, as well as its prevention and treatment.
